===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|intransitive}} To show [[mirth]], [[satisfaction]], or [[derision]], by [[peculiar]] [[movement]] of the [[muscle]]s of the [[face]], particularly of the [[mouth]], causing a [[lighting]] up of the face and [[eye]]s, and usually accompanied by the [[emission]] of [[explosive]] or [[chuckling]] [[sound]]s from the [[chest]] and [[throat]]; to [[indulge]] in [[laughter]].
#* '''c. 1602''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Troilus and Cressida}}'', act I, scene ii:
#*: But there was such laughing! Queen Hecuba '''laugh''''d that her eyes ran o'er.
#* '''1899''', {{w|Stephen Crane}}, ''[[s:Twelve O'Clock|Twelve O'Clock]]''
#*: The roars of laughter which greeted his proclamation were of two qualities; some men '''laughing''' because they knew all about cuckoo-clocks, and other men '''laughing''' because they had concluded that the eccentric Jake had been victimised by some wise child of civilisation.
#* '''1979''', {{w|Monty Python}}, ''{{w|Always Look on the Bright Side of Life}}''
#*: If life seems jolly rotten / There's something you've forgotten / And that's to '''laugh''' and smile and dance and sing.
# {{label|en|intransitive|obsolete|figuratively}} To be or appear cheerful, pleasant, mirthful, lively, or brilliant; to sparkle; to sport.
#* '''1693''', {{w|John Dryden}}, "Of the Pythagorean Philosophy", from the 15th book of Ovid's ''Metamorphoses''
#*: Then '''laughs''' the childish year, with flowerets crowned{{...}}
#* '''1734''', {{w|Alexander Pope}}, ''{{w|An Essay on Man}}'', Chapter 3
#*: In Folly’s cup ſtill '''laughs''' the bubble Joy.
# {{label|en|intransitive|followed by "at"}} To make an object of [[laughter]] or [[ridicule]]; to make fun of; to [[deride]]; to [[mock]].
#* '''1731-1735''', {{w|Alexander Pope}}, ''{{w|Moral Essays}}''
#*: No wit to flatter left of all his store, No fool to '''laugh''' at, which he valu'd more.
#* '''1890''', {{w|Oscar Wilde}}, ''{{w|The Picture of Dorian Gray}}'', Chapter 3
#*: There was something about him, Harry, that amused me. He was such a monster. You will '''laugh''' at me, I know, but I really went in and paid a whole guinea for the stage-box. To the present day I can't make out why I did so; and yet if I hadn't! – my dear Harry, if I hadn't, I would have missed the greatest romance of my life. I see you are laughing. It is horrid of you!"
#* '''1967''', {{w|The Beatles}}, ''{{w|Penny Lane}}''
#*: On the corner is a banker with a motorcar / The little children '''laugh''' at him behind his back
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[affect]] or [[influence]] by means of laughter or ridicule.
#* '''1611''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|The Tempest}}'', act II, scene i:
#*: Will you '''laugh''' me asleep, for I am very heavy?
#* '''1611''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|The Tempest}}'', act II, scene ii:
#*: I shall '''laugh''' myself to death.
# {{label|en|transitive}} To express by, or utter with, laughter.
#* '''1602''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Troilus and Cressida}}'', act I, scene iii:
#*: From his deep chest '''laughs''' out a loud applause.
#* '''1866''', {{w|Louisa May Alcott}}, ''{{w|Behind A Mask}}'' or, ''A Woman's Power''; Chapter 8
#*: Fairfax addressed her as "my lady," she '''laughed''' her musical laugh, and glanced up at a picture of Gerald with eyes full of exultation.
#* '''1906''', {{w|Jack London}}, ''{{w|Moon-Face}}''
#*: "You refuse to take me seriously," Lute said, when she had '''laughed''' her appreciation. "How can I take that Planchette rigmarole seriously?"

